To achieve this, we'll use the excellent `pugixml` library to parse the Markdown text and generate the HTML output. Here's the C++ function:
```cpp
#include <pugixml.hpp>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_node root = doc.append_child(pugi::node_type::element, "html");

    // Create the head element
    pugi::xml_node head = root.append_child(pugi::node_type::element, "head");
    head.append_child(pugi::node_type::element, "title").append_child(pugi::text, "Markdown to HTML");

    // Create the body element
    pugi::xml_node body = root.append_child(pugi::node_type::element, "body");

    // Parse the Markdown text using a Markdown parser (e.g., mdparser)
    mdparser::Parser parser;
    std::string html = parser.parse(markdown);

    // Convert the parsed HTML to a string
    pugi::xml_node parsedHtml = doc.clone_node(body, true);
    body.append_child(pugi::node_type::pcdata, parsedHtml.text());

    return parsedHtml.text();
}
```
Here's a brief explanation of the code:

1. We create a `pugi::xml_document` object to store the HTML output.
2. We create the root `<html>` element and its children `<head>` and `<body>`.
3. We parse the input Markdown text using a Markdown parser (e.g., `mdparser`) and store the parsed HTML in a string.
4. We convert the parsed HTML to a `pugi::xml_node` object using `clone_node`.
5. We append the parsed HTML node as text to the `<body>` element.
6. We return the resulting HTML text as a string.

Note that this implementation uses the `pugixml` library to work with XML nodes, and the `mdparser` library to parse the Markdown text. You'll need to include these libraries in your project and provide a compatible Markdown parser implementation.

