In TypeScript, this is known as a "cast" or "type assertion." It allows you to tell the type system that you know the value has a specific type, even if the type system can't infer it from the code.

Here's an example:
```
let value: string | number; // or any other type that has multiple possibilities

// In practice, I know this value will only be a string
value = 'hello';

// Tell the type system to treat this value as a string
value = value as string;
```
By using the `as` keyword, you're telling TypeScript to treat the value as a `string`, even though the type system initially inferred it as `string | number` (or whatever type it thought it could be).

This cast will not change the value itself, but it will change the type information associated with it. From now on, TypeScript will assume that the value is a `string`, and you'll get type errors if you try to use it as a `number`.

Note that this is a type-level guarantee, not a runtime guarantee. If you're working with data that can be manipulated or changed at runtime, it's still possible for the value to change to a different type. It's up to you to ensure that the value is indeed only of the type you've cast it to.

Also, be aware that excessive use of casts can make your code harder to maintain and understand, as it can be difficult to track which values have been cast to which types. Try to use casts judiciously and only when you're confident that you know the value's actual type.

